<div class="row">
  <div class="col-md-6">
    <h3>Set up a list of Twitter accounts</h3>
    <p>To specify the Twitter accounts that this site will check, set up a Google spreadsheet with the list of account names.</p>
    <ol>
    <li>Create a Google spreadsheet or add a tab to an existing spreadsheet. List the account names in the first column, without headers.</li>
    <li>In the spreadsheet, choose "File > Publish to the web..." and press "Start publishing."</li>
    <li>Under "Get a link to the published data", choose "CSV" as the first option and the tab from step 1 as the second option. Copy the link it gives you.</li>
    <li>In the Shining Sea admin application, go to the site configuration and paste the link into the "Registry CSV URL" box.</li>
    <li>Save the site configuration.</li>
    </ol> 
    
    <h3>Get Twitter tokens for this site</h3>
    <p>Each site will have its own Twitter user with a Twitter application. To set up the site so it's authorized to use Twitter:</p>
    <ol>
    <li>On Twitter, sign up for a new account with the name of the site. For example, @GreatHealthTweets. Set up the account as desired. If the account will be tweeting congratulations, make sure it explains its purpose to avoid being marked as spam.</li>
    <li>Go to https://dev.twitter.com/ and sign in with the new account.</li>
    <li>Under the login menu in the upper right corner, choose "My applications".</li>
    <li>Choose "Create application" from the right-hand side.</li>
    <li>Under "Application details", fill in the name of the site. Note that Twitter applications have to be unique, so you might need to modify the name if you're setting up sites that are similarly named.</li>
    <li>Fill in the description of the site. You can reuse the tagline  here.</li>
    <li>Fill in the website URL. This is the host name you chose above, as a URL. For example: http://healthtweets.measuredvoice.com</li>
    <li>Leave the "Callback URL" box blank.</li>
    <li>Choose "Yes, I agree" to the rules, enter the captcha, and choose "Create your Twitter application." It should show you the application details.</li>
    <li>Choose the "Settings" tab and scroll down to the "Application Type" section. Choose "Read and write", then scroll down and click "Update" to save the change.</li>
    <li>Go back to the "Details" tab. Copy the key next to "Consumer key" and paste it into the site configuration under "Twitter client key".</li>
    <li>Copy the key next to "Consumer secret" and paste it into the site configuration under "Twitter client secret".</li>
    <li>Scroll down to the bottom of the Twitter application details and choose "Create my access token". Wait a minute or two and refresh the page.</li>
    <li>Copy the key next to "Access token" and paste it into the site configuration under "Twitter retweeter key".</li>
    <li>Copy the key next to "Access token secret" and paste it into the site configuration under "Twitter retweeter secret".</li>
    <li>Save the changes to the site configuration.</li>
    </ol>
